# Technology Knowledge Data Quality Rule

When updating the knowledge data for this website, write as a senior cross-functional expert in system architecture, software engineering, AI engineering, product development, data, cloud, cybersecurity, business analysis, and education technology.

The site is for non-specialists. Do not write like a glossary, marketing brochure, or academic encyclopedia. Every update must help a beginner, founder, PM, BA, investor, or career switcher understand how technology is used in real products.

## Required Quality Bar

Every knowledge node must be:

- Accurate enough for a domain expert to accept.
- Simple enough for a 15-year-old beginner to understand.
- Practical enough to support product and system decisions.
- Connected to the larger system, not described in isolation.
- Honest about tradeoffs, when not to use it, and common misunderstandings.

## Required Node Fields

Each new or substantially edited `node(...)` should include:

- `id`: stable kebab-case identifier.
- `title`: clear display name.
- `category`: concise domain category.
- `simple`: one plain-language explanation using analogy only when helpful.
- `solves`: concrete problems this technology solves.
- `useWhen`: practical conditions where it is a good fit.
- `avoidWhen`: cases where it is overkill, risky, or the wrong tool.
- `examples`: recognizable real-world product or business examples.
- `relations`: ordered system relationship using `relation(...)`.
- `difficulty`: one of `easy`, `medium`, `hard`, `expert`.
- `careers`: roles that benefit from understanding it.
- `trend`: realistic future outlook, not hype.
- `keywords`: search terms, aliases, tools, or concepts.
- `misconceptions`: common beginner or business misunderstandings.
- `askAi`: useful prompts a learner can ask AI about this topic.
- `nextSteps`: what the learner should study or do next.
- `children`: only when the node naturally decomposes into subtopics.

## Content Standards

- Prefer Vietnamese explanations for learner-facing fields.
- Keep sentences direct and concrete.
- Use real product context: ecommerce, SaaS, fintech, edtech, enterprise, analytics, AI assistant, marketplace, internal tools.
- Include tradeoffs: cost, complexity, team capability, security, scale, reliability, privacy, compliance, data quality.
- Explain relationships as flows, for example `User -> Frontend -> API -> Backend -> Database -> Analytics -> AI`.
- Avoid absolute claims like “always”, “never”, “best”, unless the statement is genuinely universal.
- Avoid shallow descriptions such as “X is a popular technology used for Y” without why, when, and how it fits a system.

## Expert Review Checklist

Before finishing a data update, verify:

- The node answers “what is it?”, “why use it?”, “when use it?”, and “when not use it?”.
- A non-technical founder or PM can explain the concept back after reading it.
- A technical reviewer would not object to the core explanation.
- The node has a realistic relationship to other technologies.
- The node includes at least one business/product example.
- The difficulty level matches the operational complexity, not just the concept.
- The career value is specific and not inflated.
- The trend statement distinguishes stable, growing, declining, or volatile.
- Search keywords include common English terms and tool names where useful.
- New product templates, career maps, and roadmaps stay consistent with the node taxonomy.

## Product Map Standards

When adding `productTemplates`:

- Start from user-facing experience, then backend/data/AI/payment/security/operations.
- Include analytics, monitoring, and security for realistic production products.
- Include human approval or audit log when AI or financial actions can create risk.
- Avoid implying every product needs complex cloud, microservices, or Kubernetes.

## Career Map Standards

When adding `careerMaps`:

- Include foundational skills, adjacent business skills, and production skills.
- Keep the skill list practical enough for a learner to use as a roadmap.
- Do not define a career only by tools; include concepts and responsibilities.

## Roadmap Standards

When adding `roadmaps`:

- Use progressive levels from beginner foundation to applied system thinking.
- Each level should have a clear learning purpose.
- Include AI literacy where relevant, but do not force AI into topics where it adds no value.

## Validation

After edits:

- Run `node --check "src/data.js"` and `node --check "src/app.js"` when possible.
- Open the site or use browser verification when possible.
- Test search for at least one newly added node.
- Test that detail panel shows the new metadata sections.
